{"cursor":"6976","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"{{Infobox scientist\n| name = Orvan Walter Hess image = image_size = caption = birth_date = June 18,\n| 1906 birth_place = Baoba, Pennsylvania death_date = death_place = New Haven,\n| Connecticut citizenship = field = Medicine (obstetrics and gynaecology)\n| work_institution = Yale-New Haven Hospital Yale School of Medicine\n| alma_mater = Lafayette College, University at Buffalo doctoral_advisor =\n| doctoral_students = known_for = Penicillin Fetal heart monitor prizes =\n| AMA Scientific Achievement Award footnotes =\n}} 'Orvan Walter Hess' (June 18, 1906 â September 6, 2002) was a physician noted\nfor his early use of penicillin and the development of the fetal heart monitor.\n\nHess was born in Baoba, Pennsylvania. At the age of two, after his motherâs\ndeath, the family moved to Margaretville, New York where he grew up. Hess was\ninspired by Doctor Gordon Bostwick Maurerâwho started Margaretvilleâs first\nhospital in 1925â to study medicine. He married Dr. Maurerâs sister, Carol\nMaurer, in 1928.\n\nHess went to Lafayette College and was graduated in 1927, and received his MD\nfrom the University at Buffalo. He completed an internship at Childrenâs\nHospital in Buffalo, New York and became an obstetrician and gynecologist.\n\nFor most of his career, Hess practiced at Yale-New Haven Hospital, interrupted\nby World War II service as a surgeon in the 48th Armored Medical Battalion\nattached to the 2nd Armored Division in the invasions of North Africa, Sicily\nand Normandy.\n\nHe was clinical professor of obstetrics and gynecology at the Yale School of\nMedicine. He also served as president of the Connecticut State Medical Society,\nand director of health services for the Connecticut Welfare Department. Hess\ndied in New Haven at the age of 96.\n\nHess was predeceased by his wife Carol in 1998. He is survived by two daughters,\nDr. Katherine Halloran of Lexington, and Carolyn Westerfield of Hamden; five\ngrandchildren (including Peter Halloran); and five great-granddaughters.\n","linknr":134,"url":"Orvan_Hess","recorded":1374540637,"links":["/w/index.php?title=Orvan_Hess&action=edit","/w/index.php?title=Orvan_Hess&action=edit","//bits.wikimedia.org/favicon/wikipedia.ico","/w/opensearch_desc.php","//en.wikipedia.org/w/api.php?action=rsd","//creativecommons.org/licenses/by-sa/3.0/","/w/index.php?title=Special:RecentChanges&feed=atom","//bits.wikimedia.org/en.wikipedia.org/load.php?debug=false&lang=en&modules=ext.gadget.DRN-wizard%2CReferenceTooltips%2Ccharinsert%2Cteahouse%7Cext.rtlcite%2Cwikihiero%7Cext.uls.nojs%7Cmediawiki.legacy.commonPrint%2Cshared%7Cmw.PopUpMediaTransform%7Cskins.vector&only=styles&skin=vector&*","//bits.wikimedia.org/en.wikipedia.org/load.php?debug=false&lang=en&modules=site&only=styles&skin=vector&*","//bits.wikimedia.org/en.wikipedia.org/load.php?debug=false&lang=en&modules=startup&only=scripts&skin=vector&*","//bits.wikimedia.org/geoiplookup","//meta.wikimedia.org","#mw-navigation","#p-search","/wiki/Lackawaxen_Township,_Pennsylvania","/wiki/New_Haven,_Connecticut","//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/thumb/a/a4/Flag_of_the_United_States.svg/23px-Flag_of_the_United_States.svg.png","/wiki/United_States","/wiki/Obstetrics_and_gynaecology","/wiki/Yale-New_Haven_Hospital","/wiki/Yale_School_of_Medicine","/wiki/Alma_mater","/wiki/Lafayette_College","/wiki/University_at_Buffalo","/wiki/Penicillin","/wiki/Fetal_heart_monitor","/wiki/AMA_Scientific_Achievement_Award","/wiki/Penicillin","/wiki/Fetal_heart_monitor","/wiki/Lackawaxen_Township,_Pennsylvania","/wiki/Margaretville,_New_York","/w/index.php?title=Gordon_Bostwick_Maurer&action=edit&redlink=1","/wiki/Lafayette_College","/wiki/Doctor_of_Medicine","/wiki/University_at_Buffalo","/wiki/Buffalo,_New_York","/wiki/Obstetrician","/wiki/Gynecologist","/wiki/Yale-New_Haven_Hospital","/wiki/World_War_II","/wiki/48th_Armored_Medical_Battalion","/wiki/2nd_Armored_Division_(United_State